			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 24, 2014 4:16 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/24/opinion/nyto-avoid/nyto-avoid-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/24/opinion/nyto-avoid/nyto-avoid-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/24/opinion/nyto-avoid/nyto-avoid-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003196013" width="592" height="586" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="586"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Gabriella Demczuk for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/10/24/readers-respond-on-the-democratic-panic/" data-title="Readers Respond: On the Democratic Panic" data-description="Readers vented frustration in reaction to an editorial, âThe Democratic Panic: Alison Lundergan Grimes, Kay Hagan and Other Candidates Avoid Obama.â ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A few weeks out from Election Day 2014, some Democrats running for re-election to the United States Senate in heavily Republican states are running away from President Obamaâs record.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And boy, a lot of New York Times readers are fed up.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âJust once Iâd like to hear a Democratic Senate candidate point out that millions now have health care when they did not before,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/22/opinion/alison-lundergan-grimes-kay-hagan-and-other-candidates-avoid-obama.html?comments#permid=13121681">Robert Zisgen wrote from Mahwah, N.J.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Obama âended two wars and thus is saving blood and treasure,â Mr. Zisgen continued. âPerhaps they could mention that the stock market has done very well.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But no. Instead, when asked about their votes in support of Mr. Obamaâs agenda, some candidates are asking, âPresident who?â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So it was that readers provided a barometer of President Obamaâs low approval ratings and a sense of frustration with Democratic candidates in comments on Wednesdayâs lead editorial, â<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/22/opinion/alison-lundergan-grimes-kay-hagan-and-other-candidates-avoid-obama.html">The Democratic Panic: Alison Lundergan Grimes, Kay Hagan and Other Candidates Avoid Obama</a>.â The Times received 1,554 comments and published 1,134. A majority expressed frustration with Democratsâ lack of enthusiasm for Democratic policy. Some expressed pride in the president. And others shared the Republican hope that Democrats will end up with what they see as a well-deserved defeat.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe panicky Democratic flight away from President Obama â and from some of the partyâs most important positions â is not a surprise,â the editorial board wrote. âMr. Obama remains highly unpopular among white voters, particularly in Southern states.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Thus, itâs a challenge to assemble a winning coalition for incumbent Democrats such as Senators Mark Pryor of Arkansas; Mark Begich in Alaska; Mary Landrieu of Louisiana; and Kay Hagan of North Carolina. Alison Lundergan Grimes, a Senate candidate in Kentucky, and Michelle Nunn in Georgia are also running as centrists and eschewing comparisons to the president.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Many readers said that offering weak Democratic broth, or trying to blend in politically with Republicans, is bad strategy and poor inspiration for apathetic voters.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAs we say out here, the only thing in the middle of the road are lane lines and road kill,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/22/opinion/alison-lundergan-grimes-kay-hagan-and-other-candidates-avoid-obama.html?comments#permid=13122529">P Robison wrote from Wyoming</a>. âReally, who cares if we get Republican or Republican-Lite?â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some readers said Democrats are merely reaping the political consequences of Mr. Obamaâs unpopular policies.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThey helped vote him in and now have to live with the consequences of his failed policies, the damage done to this great country and to their own campaigns,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/22/opinion/alison-lundergan-grimes-kay-hagan-and-other-candidates-avoid-obama.html#permid=13128814">Chuck in Houston wrote</a>. âMaybe they should own up to it.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Voters on the liberal side of the spectrum expressed disappointment, but for different reasons. As the editorial board wrote: âBy not standing firmly for their own policies, Democrats send a message to voters that the unending Republican criticism of the president is legitimate.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Many readers shared that assessment. The problem is âthe failure of his colleagues in Congress and the Democratic Party to stand besideâ the president, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/22/opinion/alison-lundergan-grimes-kay-hagan-and-other-candidates-avoid-obama.html?comments#permid=13123945">Colleen Gillard wrote from Cambridge, Mass.</a> âCanât think of another Democratic president in history who has been so abandoned.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Others advised Democrats to âget a backbone,â as one reader put it.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A few readers pointed out that Democrats face special challenges in off-year elections, when they must appeal to centrists, as Democratic voters historically have turned out <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/02/upshot/bursting-the-democrats-midterm-turnout-bubble.html?abt=0002&amp;abg=1">at lower rates</a>Â than Republicans.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That dynamic among likely voters weakens the appeal of the Affordable Care Act, for example, which the editorial board described as âone of the most far-reaching and beneficial laws to have been passed by Congress in years.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI suspect part of the problem is that the beneficiaries of Obamacare are disproportionately members of groups (young, low-income, etc.) regarded as having a relatively low propensity to vote, particularly in mid-terms,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/22/opinion/alison-lundergan-grimes-kay-hagan-and-other-candidates-avoid-obama.html?comments#permid=13122027">Paul McDonough wrote from California</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Several readers said Democrats need a fundamental change in tactics. âThe Democrats are running on fear rather than expressing outrage, as President Harry Truman did so successfully,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/22/opinion/alison-lundergan-grimes-kay-hagan-and-other-candidates-avoid-obama.html?comments#permid=13122293">Paul wrote from Long Island</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some said Democrats making weak policy arguments are just laying the groundwork for policy failure.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âCowards,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/22/opinion/alison-lundergan-grimes-kay-hagan-and-other-candidates-avoid-obama.html?comments#permid=13121854">Tom J. in Berwyn wrote</a>. âEven if they win, we get a Senate full of more cowards, who let a Republican minority steamroll over everything.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Democratsâ sense of being dispirited ran through many comments.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThese Democratic politicians stand for self perpetuation without regard to integrity,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/22/opinion/alison-lundergan-grimes-kay-hagan-and-other-candidates-avoid-obama.html?comments#permid=13125506">Corrinna in Boulder, Colo., wrote</a>. âI can barely bring myself to vote.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Still, some readers agreed with the editorial boardâs view that the stimulus bill was vital in pulling the country out of the recession, and âthere is much that is going right in this country.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âLike him or not, the economy is steadily improving and more Americans have health insurance,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/22/opinion/alison-lundergan-grimes-kay-hagan-and-other-candidates-avoid-obama.html?comments#permid=13124516:13125104">Margaret Bradley in Fayetteville, Ga., wrote</a>. âIâm sure those auto workers were happy to get their jobs back.â</p>
	</div>
